    <!-- SECTION 1 -->
    <h2>The Weight Loss You Can See — And the Loss You Can't</h2>

    <p>GLP-1 receptor agonists — semaglutide (Ozempic, Wegovy), tirzepatide (Mounjaro, Zepbound) — suppress appetite and slow gastric emptying. They work. Men who've struggled for years are losing 15–25% of their bodyweight. The results look impressive on the scale.</p>

    <p>But the scale doesn't tell you what's actually being lost.</p>

    <p>Multiple clinical studies examining body composition during GLP-1 treatment have found that 25–40% of the total weight lost comes from lean mass — muscle, bone density, and organ tissue — rather than fat. In the STEP and SURMOUNT trials, lean mass loss was substantial enough that researchers flagged it as a clinical concern requiring dietary intervention.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <div class="warning-label">⚠ The Hidden Risk</div>
      <p>Losing 30 lbs on Ozempic sounds like a win. But if 10–12 of those pounds were muscle, you haven't just lost weight — you've accelerated the very aging process you were trying to reverse. Muscle is the metabolic engine. Less muscle means slower metabolism, weaker bones, higher fall risk, and a harder time keeping the weight off long-term. This is how men end up "skinny-fat" — weighing less on the scale but carrying a higher body fat percentage because their muscle vanished.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 2 -->
    <h2>Why Men Over 40 Are at Greater Risk</h2>

    <p>This isn't a concern distributed equally across all GLP-1 users. Men over 40 face a compounding problem:</p>

    <div class="card-grid">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔬</div>
        <h4>Anabolic Resistance</h4>
        <p>After 40, your muscles require more protein — and a larger leucine (the amino acid that acts as the "on switch" for muscle building) dose per meal — to trigger the same muscle-building response that 25-year-olds get from half the protein. GLP-1-driven calorie restriction amplifies this problem.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📉</div>
        <h4>Pre-existing Sarcopenia Risk</h4>
        <p>Men lose 3–8% of muscle per decade after 30, with that rate accelerating after 60. You're starting this race behind — rapid weight loss without protein protection pushes you further back.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🤢</div>
        <h4>Nausea Suppresses Protein Foods</h4>
        <p>GLP-1 side effects — nausea, fullness, food aversion — often hit protein-dense foods hardest. Many men find themselves defaulting to crackers and broth, not chicken and eggs.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🏋️</div>
        <h4>Reduced Training Capacity</h4>
        <p>Calorie restriction combined with GLP-1 side effects often leads to reduced workout intensity or frequency — removing the second major protective factor for muscle preservation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 3 -->
    <h2>What the Research Actually Shows</h2>

    <p>The clinical conversation around GLP-1 and muscle loss has accelerated rapidly. Here's the honest picture from what's been published:</p>

    <table class="comparison-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Scenario</th>
          <th>Typical Lean Mass Lost</th>
          <th>Risk Level</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>GLP-1 alone, no protein focus</td>
