    <!-- SECTION 4 -->
    <h2>Why Appetite Suppression Makes Protein Tracking Non-Negotiable</h2>

    <p>Here's the trap: GLP-1s work by making you feel full and satisfied on far fewer calories. That's the mechanism. But "feeling full" doesn't distinguish between getting enough protein and getting enough crackers.</p>

    <p>Men on GLP-1s frequently report eating 800–1,200 calories a day and feeling perfectly comfortable. At those intake levels, hitting 100g+ of protein requires intentional planning — not just eating when you're hungry. You'll rarely be hungry.</p>

    <p>This is the exact scenario where not tracking protein leads to exactly the outcome you're trying to avoid: losing muscle while the scale shows you "winning."</p>

    <p>I'm 64, lifelong active, not on these drugs — but I know what it looks like when protein intake drops without anyone realizing it. You feel a little weaker at the gym. Stairs are slightly harder. Recovery takes longer. By the time it's obvious, months of muscle have already been lost.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 5 -->
    <h2>The Two Non-Negotiables While on GLP-1s</h2>

    <h3>1. Hit Your Protein Number Every Day</h3>
    <p>Not most days. Every day. When you're eating 1,000–1,200 calories on GLP-1s, there's no room for low-protein days. Protein has to come first — literally structure meals around it. Eggs and Greek yogurt for breakfast. Chicken or fish at lunch. A protein-forward dinner. Supplement with cottage cheese or a shake if the numbers aren't adding up.</p>
    <p>The 30g-per-meal rule matters more on GLP-1s than it does off them. Your muscles need a sufficient leucine threshold per meal to trigger protein synthesis — spreading 60g across six small snacks isn't equivalent to hitting 30g three times.</p>

    <h3>2. Keep Resistance Training in the Picture</h3>
    <p>Even reduced-intensity resistance training signals to your body that muscle is needed. It doesn't have to be heavy. But it has to be consistent. Lifting while on GLP-1s with adequate protein is the closest thing there is to a guarantee that your weight loss comes from fat, not muscle.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <div class="warning-label">📋 Talk to Your Doctor</div>
      <p>This post is informational — not medical advice. If you're on a GLP-1 medication, discuss protein targets, body composition monitoring, and resistance training with your prescribing physician. Many doctors are now recommending DEXA scans before and during GLP-1 treatment to track lean mass directly.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 6 -->
    <h2>How to Track Protein While on GLP-1s (Without Making It a Second Job)</h2>

    <p>The last thing you need while managing nausea, food aversions, and a radically different appetite is a complicated tracking app demanding you log every macro and micronutrient. That's the recipe for giving up entirely.</p>

    <p>What works: track one number. Just protein. Every day. Know your target (use the table above or the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-calculator-men-over-40/">protein calculator</a>). Log what you eat. See the number. That's it.</p>

    <p>Most men on GLP-1s eat the same 8–10 foods repeatedly — whatever their stomach tolerates well. That actually makes tracking easier, not harder. You learn your foods fast. Entry gets faster. The feedback becomes automatic.</p>

    <p>The goal isn't perfection. It's visibility. You can't protect what you can't see.</p>

